ffects-of-antimuscarinics","fullItemName":"Adverse effects of antimuscarinics"},{"id":"c4ecff94-72a7-5298-9eff-aa0f014bd0d2","slug":"administering-drugs-via-syringe-driver","fullItemName":"Administering drugs via syringe driver"}]},{"id":"fc7ec3a1-6164-5fce-ae68-ea76a7e7ed95","fullItemName":"Supporting evidence","slug":"supporting-evidence","subChapters":[{"id":"f0bd35d1-28aa-5304-bbae-6437a5cff4f8","slug":"antimuscarinics-for-respiratory-secretions","fullItemName":"Antimuscarinics for respiratory secretions"}]},{"id":"13aa02e3-ed7e-5603-b3cf-c8c77f16c1ad","fullItemName":"How this topic was developed","slug":"how-this-topic-was-developed","subChapters":[{"id":"9720e3b4-46d0-5fc7-a0db-be67e6db6bfa","slug":"search-strategy","fullItemName":"Search strategy"},{"id":"92414bd0-2c9f-584a-badf-10b45f202fc3","slug":"stakeholder-engagement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"42fc232e-bba3-513f-a5d9-15378200e570","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"68c17f61-0db1-544c-a0b5-b14bb9ce5c5c","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"bf6037b2-67c3-5d11-ae91-c606813ad76d","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"741bbef8-7d2e-53e4-ae09-0cb22ef8d617","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"6f40bc41-9977-54ec-b25f-77e34d1c3cac","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management"},"subChapters":[{"id":"9c164817-c331-5b68-81cb-f7134e1955ef","slug":"assessment","fullItemName":"Assessment","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 56a219f6-7739-4ca7-882d-e5fc54089fd4 --><h3>How should I assess a person with respiratory secretions in palliative care?</h3><!-- end field 56a219f6-7739-4ca7-882d-e5fc54089fd4 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 080897ed-6a3e-44e6-95d1-2d6d4b48c3fa --><!-- begin field 5079a288-8e36-481b-90d4-98fc78ec64e9 --><ul><li><strong>Consider </strong><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-secretions/background-information/why-do-secretions-accumulate/\">why secretions have accumulated</a><strong>.</strong></li><li><strong>Assess for the likely causes</strong> of noisy respiratory secretions in people in the last days of life. Establish whether the noise has an impact on the dying person or those important to them. Reassure them that, although the noise can be distressing, it is unlikely to cause discomfort. Be prepared to talk about any fears or concerns they may have.</li><li><strong>Estimate the likely prognosis, if possible.</strong><ul><li>Estimating the prognosis helps in the planning of appropriate treatment and care. For more information, see the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-general-issues/\">Palliative care - general issues</a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>In the terminal phase, explore the understanding and needs of the person (if appropriate) and their family.</strong><ul><li>Exploring the understanding and needs of the person and their family is important, in order to make the situation as comfortable as possible.</li><li>It is essential to recognize the signs of dying in order to appropriately care for people at the end of life. In the final days of life, investigations are generally not appropriate and where appropriate this should be discussed with the person and their family and carers.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Consider non-pharmacological measures</strong> to manage noisy respiratory or pharyngeal secretions, to reduce any distress in people at the end of life.</li><li><strong>People are likely to be in the terminal phase of their illness when they:</strong><ul><li>Deteriorate day by day or faster because of their underlying condition.</li><li>Express a realization that they are dying.</li><li>Have reduced cognition, and are drowsy or comatose.</li><li>Are bed-bound.</li><li>Take little food or fluid, and have difficulty taking oral medication.</li><li>Are peripherally cyanosed and cold.</li><li>Have an altered breathing pattern</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 5079a288-8e36-481b-90d4-98fc78ec64e9 --><!-- end item 080897ed-6a3e-44e6-95d1-2d6d4b48c3fa -->","subChapters":[{"id":"ea626bf3-86e2-515b-b2c3-cf4fef5cf853","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-d74","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":4,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 98e144ba-f46d-40b2-b4d1-4cea7d60bcd6 --><h4>Basis for recommendation</h4><!-- end field 98e144ba-f46d-40b2-b4d1-4cea7d60bcd6 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item d7406c73-d353-49a7-bd09-60c04255d488 --><!-- begin field 8f816558-e579-4f51-9d37-01333bc8fa5f --><p>These recommendations are based on guidance from the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-secretions/references/\">NICE, 2004</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-secretions/references/\">NICE, 2015</a>] and expert opinion [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-secretions/references/\">Regnard, 2010</a>].</p><ul><li>Pooling of saliva is the most common cause of rattling breathing in a person who is terminally ill [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-secretions/references/\">Twycross, 2014</a>].</li><li>The information on recognizing the terminal phase is based on expert opinion from palliative care resources that were developed from clinical experience [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-secretions/references/\">Morita et al, 1998</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-secretions/references/\">Regnard, 2010</a>].</li></ul><!-- end field 8f816558-e579-4f51-9d37-01333bc8fa5f --><!-- end item d7406c73-d353-49a7-bd09-60c04255d488 -->","subChapters":[]}]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}